.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/adrs/adr-001.md:1:# ADR-001: Treat SOUL.md as an Optional Persona Artifact
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/adrs/adr-001.md:13:AGH already has a structured agent definition in `AGENT.md`, capability catalogs, runtime context assembly, task leases, session supervision, and AGH Network presence. Reference systems use `SOUL.md` as a persona/identity artifact, but they separate it from runtime liveness and task ownership. The AGH design must preserve existing runtime authorities and avoid a second operational state model hidden in Markdown.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/adrs/adr-001.md:17:AGH will support an optional `SOUL.md` file beside each agent's `AGENT.md`. `SOUL.md` is an authored persona and behavioral identity artifact. It uses Markdown with optional strict frontmatter plus a narrative body. It may define only persona/identity behavior such as role, communication style, decision principles, behavioral constraints, collaboration style, and memory policy hints.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/adrs/adr-001.md:19:`SOUL.md` must not define fields owned by `AGENT.md`, config, capabilities, task/runtime state, scheduler behavior, lease heartbeat, session activity, or AGH Network presence. Unknown frontmatter fields and forbidden operational fields fail validation.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/adrs/adr-001.md:21:If `SOUL.md` is absent, the agent remains valid with `present=false`. If `SOUL.md` exists but is malformed, oversized beyond the hard parser limit, outside the allowed path, or declares forbidden operational authority, agent profile loading fails closed and session creation must not proceed. CLI, HTTP, and UDS surfaces return the same typed diagnostic shape for the same failure class.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/adrs/adr-001.md:27:- **Description**: Add persona fields directly to `AGENT.md` and do not introduce `SOUL.md`.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/adrs/adr-001.md:30:- **Why rejected**: The user wants `SOUL.md` as an optional additional file, and competitor evidence shows a separate persona file improves authoring clarity.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/adrs/adr-001.md:32:### Alternative 2: Make SOUL.md the Agent Definition
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/adrs/adr-001.md:34:- **Description**: Let `SOUL.md` replace or override agent identity, tools, routing, and runtime fields.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/adrs/adr-001.md:37:- **Why rejected**: `SOUL.md` is persona, not provider/tool/runtime authority.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/adrs/adr-001.md:54:- Authors may try to place operational instructions in `SOUL.md`; strict validation and documentation must reject that.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:5:AGH will support an optional `SOUL.md` file beside an agent's existing `AGENT.md`. `SOUL.md` is an authored persona and behavioral identity artifact: it describes how an agent should think, communicate, collaborate, apply principles, and relate to memory. It is not a runtime state file, not a heartbeat file, not task ownership, not capability declaration, and not orchestration policy.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:12:- `SOUL.md` is optional and scoped to persona/identity.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:13:- AGH validates `SOUL.md` with strict frontmatter and reserved-section checks.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:17:- AGH provides managed `SOUL.md` authoring with validation, compare-and-swap writes, revision history, rollback, and auditability.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:19:- `HEARTBEAT.md` is explicitly deferred to a separate operational wake/heartbeat spec.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:21:MVP boundary: implementation steps 1-12 add optional `SOUL.md` parsing, validation, managed authoring, prompt inclusion, resolved read models, session/task provenance, extension Host API read/write actions, CLI/API/UDS manageability, contract codegen, docs, and verification. Post-MVP work includes typed persona overlays, extension-authored overlay layers, any `HEARTBEAT.md` or wake policy behavior, network-wide persona propagation, and richer web editing UI.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:25:- Add optional `SOUL.md` support without weakening the existing agent spec.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:28:- Let agents and explicitly-granted extensions create, update, delete, inspect, validate, list history, and roll back `SOUL.md` through the same managed authoring service.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:34:- Do not implement `HEARTBEAT.md`.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:38:- Do not let `SOUL.md` define provider, command, model, tools, toolsets, permissions, hooks, capabilities, MCP servers, config, tasks, leases, network membership, or scheduler behavior.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:45:`SOUL.md` enters the same broad profile-resolution path as `AGENT.md`, but with narrower authority.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:52:SOUL.md |
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:62:`AGENT.md` continues to own executable and operational fields. `SOUL.md` contributes only a validated persona block and structured metadata. The resolved soul is immutable for a session unless an explicit refresh operation is requested and accepted.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/_techspec_soul.md:66:- `internal/config` owns `SOUL.md` parsing, frontmatter validation, digesting, source-path normalization, atomic file authoring, compare-and-swap checks, and `SoulDef` / `ResolvedSoul` construction. No session, task, API, CLI, extension, or web code parses or writes `SOUL.md` directly.
