.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/memory/task_09.md:11:- Wake decisions fail closed when current config disables Heartbeat, no valid policy exists, a snapshot envelope is invalid, active/quiet-hour policy blocks the wake, session health is not wake-eligible, cooldown/coalescing applies, or the prompt gate is busy.
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/qa/peer-review-message-round1.md:7:      "issue": "Claim-time soul snapshot semantics are ambiguous in two load-bearing ways. (1) The spec asserts that `ClaimNextRun` writes soul provenance to `task_runs.metadata_json` and that the active digest is snapshotted 'again at task-run claim time' (ADR-003), but never names *whose* soul is captured: the claiming session's existing `soul_snapshot_id`, the agent definition resolved fresh from disk, or some other source. (2) It does not say whether `ClaimNextRun` performs file I/O / validation / digest computation inside the claim transaction (which runs under `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` per L-003) or merely copies a precomputed digest from the session row. Resolving `SOUL.md` from inside the only authoritative claim primitive risks turning a hot-path atomic transition into a slow, fail-prone, FS-bound operation, and risks splitting claim semantics for runs that have no parent session (scheduler-created or orphan-recovered).",
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/qa/peer-review-message-round1.md:9:      "suggested_fix": "Add an explicit subsection under 'Lease And Safety Invariants' titled 'Claim-Time Soul Provenance' that states: (a) the soul digest written to `task_runs.metadata_json` MUST be sourced from the claiming session's `sessions.soul_snapshot_id` row already loaded before the claim transaction opens — `ClaimNextRun` performs no `SOUL.md` resolution, no parsing, no path traversal, no FS I/O, and no validation; (b) for runs claimed without a session (e.g., scheduler-detached future cases), the metadata block omits the soul provenance entirely with a typed sentinel; (c) the invariant is added to the numbered list as 'Soul provenance is read-only inside ClaimNextRun and never blocks or extends the claim transaction'."
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/qa/peer-review-message-round1.md:28:      "issue": "Lease invariant 9 says 'Invalid SOUL.md fails closed for the affected agent profile.' This phrase is load-bearing but ambiguous: 'fails closed' could mean (a) the agent profile cannot be loaded and session creation fails, or (b) the agent loads but the soul is dropped with diagnostics, or (c) the agent loads with a partial/last-good soul. Each option produces a materially different runtime contract for both autonomous and manual surfaces, and the contract must be the same for both per L-004.",
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/qa/peer-review-message-round1.md:29:      "rationale": "L-004: manual operator paths and autonomous paths converge on the same primitives; an ambiguous failure mode here will produce different behavior in `agh agent soul validate <agent>` (manual) vs `agh session create` (which may be triggered manually or autonomously). L-006: greenfield prefers a hard, observable failure to silent fallback. The spec's own 'never silently drop forbidden operational declarations' line implies (a), but 'agent profile' is not a session.",
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/qa/peer-review-message-round1.md:30:      "suggested_fix": "Add an explicit table to 'Prompt And Runtime Behavior' enumerating each failure class (forbidden field, oversized body, malformed frontmatter, path traversal attempt, missing file, parse error) and the resulting behavior across (i) `agh agent soul validate`, (ii) `agh agent soul inspect`, (iii) session creation, (iv) `ClaimNextRun`, and (v) refresh. State that session creation MUST fail closed when the agent's `SOUL.md` exists but is invalid, and that the manual CLI surface returns the same typed diagnostic struct."
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/qa/peer-review-message-round1.md:42:      "issue": "Refresh re-resolves `SOUL.md`, validates it, computes a digest, opens the snapshot store, possibly writes a new snapshot, updates the session row, and emits an audit event. None of this is bounded by the request lifetime spec, and the spec does not say whether the work runs under `c.Request.Context()` or detached. If the client disconnects mid-refresh, the session row may be left in a half-updated state.",
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/qa/peer-review-message-round1.md:98:      "section": "HEARTBEAT.md Decision",
.compozy/tasks/agent-soul/qa/peer-review-message-round1.md:110:  "summary": "The spec is structurally solid — MVP boundary, architectural boundaries, side-table-vs-JSON decision, numbered safety invariants, and a clean HEARTBEAT.md deferral are all present — but it under-specifies the most load-bearing interaction (soul provenance attached to `ClaimNextRun`) and leaves three Go types referenced by interfaces undefined. Resolve the claim-time semantics (B-001), define the missing types (B-002), bind the migration to a specific SQLite database with fresh + reopen tests (B-003), disambiguate 'fails closed' (B-004), enumerate UDS parity (B-005), and bound refresh lifetime (B-006); the spec then becomes ready to drive `_tasks.md` generation."
